{{Orphan|date=February 2009}}
A '''tragic carpet''', according to the ''Concise Oxford Companion to the Theatre'', is the green cloth that was spread on the [[stage (theatre)|stage]] in seventeenth century plays for the [[actor]]s to "die" on so they would not dirty their clothes.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Concise Oxford Companion to the Theatre|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=1979|pages=559|isbn=978-0-19-866136-8}}</ref>

